The paper deals with the capacity analysis of a communication channel with a unique input constraint due to energy harvesting. This input constraint is random, instantaneous, and influenced by the full history of inputs and energy harvesting process. Therefore, the paper is likely to belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category. Additionally, the paper deals with the optimization of achievable rates for channels with Markov energy harvesting processes, which suggests that it may also belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category. The paper also deals with the observation of energy information causally at the transmitter, which suggests that it may belong to the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-category. The paper may also belong to the Multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category as it deals with the transmission of symbols with limited energy. Finally, the paper may belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category as it uses techniques developed for channels with side information and finite state channels.
